WEBVTT

00:09.020 --> 00:12.960
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.620 --> 00:33.900
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.560 --> 00:38.200
And here are your hosts.

00:42.220 --> 00:44.120
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson.

00:44.620 --> 00:48.020
In addition to being an author, Terry Carr is one of Science Fiction's premier editors.

00:48.320 --> 00:51.520
We asked him how he got hooked on science fiction back in the late 1940s.

00:52.820 --> 00:56.100
Oh, that's kind of interesting.

00:56.940 --> 01:00.100
Most people don't believe this story, but I actually discovered science fiction when

01:00.100 --> 01:01.600
I was wandering around at Garbage Dump.

01:03.180 --> 01:08.180
There was a garbage dump a few blocks from our house, and I liked it at that time.

01:08.180 --> 01:10.340
I was about ten or eleven or something.

01:11.400 --> 01:14.720
Sometimes friends and I would just go down and look around to see what people were throwing

01:14.720 --> 01:15.020
out.

01:16.020 --> 01:20.600
And one day, among the things we found, people had thrown out were a couple of old cult magazines

01:21.180 --> 01:22.040
from the year before.

01:23.640 --> 01:27.960
Amazing stories, and I think there was one amazing story and one fantastic adventure,

01:28.180 --> 01:29.840
those being companion magazines.

01:31.000 --> 01:34.560
We grabbed those and brought them home, and I loved them.

01:34.620 --> 01:35.420
I got hooked right there.

01:36.460 --> 01:40.580
After publishing a couple early novels and some short stories, Carr began his editing

01:40.580 --> 01:41.460
career at Ace Books.

01:41.940 --> 01:44.300
We asked him if he could tell us exactly what he did for Ace.

01:45.400 --> 01:55.260
Yeah, in 1964, I went to work for Ace Books as an editorial assistant, which actually

01:55.260 --> 01:58.300
meant that I was low-man on the totem pole there.

01:58.420 --> 02:04.940
I was simply somebody who copied the manuscript, went over them to make sure the spelling was

02:04.940 --> 02:06.260
correct and things like that.

02:06.480 --> 02:07.640
There were no typographical errors.

02:08.840 --> 02:17.000
And then proofread the books before they actually got published to make sure once again that

02:17.000 --> 02:19.060
there were no typographical errors in the type setting.

02:19.820 --> 02:25.840
I would write blurbs, cover copy, kind of, you know, the things that are written on the

02:25.840 --> 02:31.820
front and back covers of paperback books to try to get you to be interested enough in

02:31.820 --> 02:32.540
the book to buy it.

02:34.600 --> 02:39.100
And at the same time, I was reading a number of submissions that were coming in.

02:39.280 --> 02:42.340
If I saw something good, I would pass it on to the editor, who was found at Wollinheim.

02:50.920 --> 02:54.800
Carr says he then began to make suggestions for improving and expanding the Ace Line of

02:54.800 --> 02:57.280
Science Fiction books, and he worked his way up in the company.

02:58.380 --> 03:03.560
Ace Books then did start doing a number of things that I had suggested, so that I began

03:03.560 --> 03:05.340
getting this and that promotion.

03:05.820 --> 03:09.440
And I think after about the first three years, I became a senior editor there.

03:12.420 --> 03:17.000
And began a series called the Ace Science Fiction Specials, which was very much a departure

03:17.000 --> 03:22.580
for Ace Books in particular, but for the entire field for that matter, because it was specifically

03:22.580 --> 03:28.980
designed to publish adult science fiction novels, not simply a juvenile adventure, but

03:28.980 --> 03:36.820
serious novels using the science fiction genre as its format, and packaged uniformly so that

03:36.820 --> 03:42.860
people would be able to recognize a new book in the series when it came out, and packaged

03:42.860 --> 03:48.060
in such a way that, you know, it didn't have monsters chasing half-naked women on the covers.

03:48.060 --> 03:55.920
We had very good artwork by a team of artists called Leo and Diane Dillon, who later won

03:55.920 --> 04:00.920
a Hugo Award and won two Caldecott Awards, and God knows what else they were, extremely good artists.

04:02.260 --> 04:06.940
I also began anthologizing very early when I started there.

04:07.660 --> 04:15.080
Don Wollinheim and I were collaborating on an anthology, an annual anthology called World's Best Science Fiction.

04:17.160 --> 04:23.940
And I gradually branched out from that, since I had begun to have my name on anthologies.

04:24.540 --> 04:29.440
I began to do others for Double Day and Flosset Books and so on.

04:30.620 --> 04:36.240
And that was actually how I got my start doing anthologies, was the work that I was doing in Ace Books.

04:37.700 --> 04:42.180
Some of the anthologies Carr does include the annual Universe series of original science fiction,

04:42.180 --> 04:47.940
which he originated in 1971, and the Best Science Fiction of the Year series, which he began in 1972.

04:48.680 --> 04:52.420
We'll talk to Terry Carr next time about what it's like to edit anthologies of science fiction.

04:59.520 --> 05:04.380
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association,

05:05.100 --> 05:07.980
produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

