Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:17.280 --> 06:22.380
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:25.220 --> 06:26.680
And here are your hosts.

06:30.900 --> 06:32.120
This is David Carson.

06:32.360 --> 06:33.060
And Daryl Lane.

06:33.320 --> 06:36.400
Each year, Terry Carr edits two of the best known anthologies in science fiction.

06:36.840 --> 06:41.680
One is the Universe series, begun in 1971, which is an anthology of original science fiction.

06:41.680 --> 06:46.200
We ask Carr the difference to an author between selling his story to a monthly science fiction magazine,

06:46.660 --> 06:48.420
or selling it to an anthology like Universe.

06:49.180 --> 06:50.640
There are all sorts of differences.

06:54.180 --> 06:56.660
They're both artistic and monetary differences.

06:57.480 --> 07:05.760
For one thing, if you sell to a magazine, then the money that you get from the magazine is simply the payment for that use of the story.

07:06.500 --> 07:11.920
If you sell it to an original anthology, that's going into a book, and you get an advance payment.

07:13.600 --> 07:15.700
But after that, you get a share of the royalties.

07:15.700 --> 07:19.600
If the book sells well, then there will be additional earnings on the book.

07:20.500 --> 07:27.280
And the individual authors will continue to make money for years thereafter, and indeed they do on Universe, because it does sell pretty well.

07:28.400 --> 07:39.840
So your chances of making money on your story are at least as good, I would say, in the original anthologies as they are in the science fiction magazines.

07:41.060 --> 07:48.640
Aside from that, there's also the fact that a lot of writers simply like to have their work appear in book form,

07:48.680 --> 07:54.400
because they know it's going to be around to be read longer than a magazine will be.

07:54.400 --> 07:58.940
It'll stay in better shape, and it'll be in library or something like that.

08:07.060 --> 08:12.680
The best science fiction of the year, which Carr began in 1972 with Donald Walheim, is a different sort of anthology.

08:13.280 --> 08:16.560
It consists of stories published in science fiction magazines during the year.

08:17.020 --> 08:20.560
Carr reads all the magazines, then selects those stories he considers to be the best.

08:20.560 --> 08:24.980
But he says that there are certain problems that he has to solve when he actually starts putting the stories together.

08:51.580 --> 09:02.320
And if it should ever happen, for instance, that I think the best 15 stories of the year, however many it takes, are all time travel stories, for instance.

09:03.060 --> 09:06.600
I'm not going to publish a whole book, but with time travel stories, that's just silly.

09:07.040 --> 09:10.400
Again, people would get tired of reading so many time travel stories in one book.

09:11.600 --> 09:13.480
So I try to mix up the themes, too.

09:14.700 --> 09:17.460
Carr explains the particular needs an anthology fulfills.

09:18.620 --> 09:27.180
As best I know, anthology fills the need for people who want to read good science fiction short stories, novelettes, novellas, whatever.

09:28.060 --> 09:32.680
People who want to read something other than a novel.

09:33.660 --> 09:42.680
Probably people who want to have something that they can dip into from time to time, rather than sitting down and reading the whole thing straight through as they would a novel.

09:44.140 --> 09:49.640
There's a different psychology between reading novels and short stories, and most people do prefer to read novels.

09:49.800 --> 09:54.840
They always sell better than anthologies or single author short story collections.

09:56.820 --> 09:59.940
But there are people who like the short stories. I do, for instance.

10:01.320 --> 10:03.260
And they're the people who buy these.

10:05.060 --> 10:10.680
On a re-pandemology, the attraction, I think, is that these stories have been doubly screened.

10:10.680 --> 10:14.700
There are stories that were good enough in the first place to sell to the magazine.

10:15.680 --> 10:19.520
And then beyond that, there are the best stories from the magazine.

10:19.940 --> 10:27.960
So the people who pick up an anthology can reasonably expect that that is going to contain more good stories than the average issue of a science fiction magazine.

10:28.920 --> 10:32.940
This isn't always true. There's very bad anthologies and there's very good issues in magazines.

10:34.080 --> 10:36.280
But by and large, that is the case, I think.

10:37.040 --> 10:41.640
Terry Carr also writes fine science fiction. Next time we'll talk to him about some of his own writing.

10:49.340 --> 10:57.880
