24:00.700 --> 24:02.080
And David Carson.

24:05.160 --> 24:09.260
One of his better known creations is the mysterious millipede in the novel Cirque.

24:09.540 --> 24:14.920
The dance of the changer in the three is one of those stories.

24:18.520 --> 24:23.500
I had been reading of all people Roger's Alarm, we've seen him mention him a lot here.

24:25.600 --> 24:32.720
And Roger at that time, this was in the late 60s, was working a lot with mythology in his science fiction.

24:33.520 --> 24:40.840
And I got interested in his work, I loved his work, and I was always interested in mythology itself.

24:42.660 --> 24:55.980
And it occurred to me that mythology tells a whole lot about the fears, the hopes, the beliefs of humanity.

24:56.840 --> 25:04.880
And that indeed, if any alien creature ever came to this planet and wanted to find out something about what makes humanity tick,

25:05.000 --> 25:07.640
they could do far worse than to study some of our myths.

25:08.700 --> 25:13.780
And I suddenly just, there was a little psectic that goes on in your head and I turned that around and said,

25:13.860 --> 25:21.600
well, I like to think and write about aliens, and it's very difficult to write about an alien from the inside,

25:21.600 --> 25:27.140
because I personally believe that aliens are inexplicable to us, but we're never going to understand this fully.

25:28.660 --> 25:37.260
So I thought, possibly a good way of dealing with the portrayal of an alien or an entire alien race would be to do it

25:37.260 --> 25:45.420
circuitously by telling an alien myth. And that is exactly what the dance of the changer in the three years, of course, is an alien myth.

25:45.940 --> 25:50.020
And the myth itself is supposed to tell you a lot about the psychology of the race.

25:55.520 --> 25:58.520
We never do understand the psychology of the aliens in the story.

25:59.120 --> 26:04.980
The human narrator describes certain actions and some of the dialogue of the aliens, but the significance of all of this is never clear.

26:05.460 --> 26:12.400
The climax of the story occurs when the aliens, who are creatures of pure energy, inexplicably destroy almost all the humans on their planet.

26:12.740 --> 26:17.160
And they do it without malice, while they are performing one of the ritual dances that belong to their mythology.

26:17.160 --> 26:22.160
We ask our if there is perhaps some reason for this massacre, something we missed in reading the story.

26:47.160 --> 26:54.960
We could write something that made no sense, whatever. So the myth itself, of course, is kind of a self-canceling myth.

26:55.940 --> 27:05.320
If you actually analyze it, there's a certain circularity to it. It has a dramatic coherence.

27:07.020 --> 27:16.840
But it's not a story that we would ever tell about ourselves that would resonate with the human psyche.

27:18.240 --> 27:28.940
And I wanted to end the story with something totally inexplicable happening, just to underscore and emphasize the fact that these creatures were aliens.

27:29.360 --> 27:36.600
And I wanted it to be something that none of us is going to understand, and that meant inevitably that I had to be sure I didn't understand it either.

27:37.720 --> 27:44.340
One of the points of the story then seems to be that humans could never understand an alien species. We ask Tarif, his interpretation was correct.

27:45.320 --> 27:50.620
Yeah, that was the basic point. I've been trying to make that point in a number of my stories.

27:50.620 --> 27:58.000
This is another one that I wrote earlier called Top Friends, which makes much the same point, but not quite as dramatically as that did.

27:59.340 --> 28:09.000
Carr's premise in the Dance of the Changer in the Three is an interesting one, very different from the common science fiction notions of aliens as either hostile bug-eyed monsters or as creatures we can become close to.

